<div id="content_text">

<br/>

<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <strong>October 30,  2007</strong><p><i>Today@UCI</i><p><strong>To the rescue</strong><p><strong>By Kathryn Bold</strong><br><p><i>Led by Jay Lickfett, Calit2 creates a disaster Web portal that helps Ontario survive recent wildfires</i> (10.30.2007)<p>When one of the Southern California firestorms broke out in Ontario the night of Sunday, Oct. 21, the city&rsquo;s emergency response team turned to Jay Lickfett, lead software engineer at UCI&rsquo;s Calit2 RESCUE Project, for help. <p>Lickfett had developed a disaster Web portal for Ontario that allowed emergency responders to provide the public with real-time information in a crisis, and now his system faced its first real test.<p>&ldquo;When the fire started, we knew we had to get our portal working,&rdquo; says Ontario Emergency Manager Jacob Green &rsquo;05. Fortunately Green, who got a degree in social sciences from UCI, had connections.<p>&ldquo;I called Jay at his home in Irvine and he was in our emergency operations center in 45 minutes. He got there around 10 p.m. and he didn&rsquo;t leave until 10 a.m. He helped our public information officers and command staff get information out to the community. He was phenomenal.&rdquo;<p>Ontario&rsquo;s residents used the portal&rsquo;s interactive maps to check on the fire&rsquo;s progress, find out which streets were closed, monitor mandatory evacuations and locate evacuation centers.<p>&ldquo;The system performed perfectly. And Jay made sure everything was up and running,&rdquo; Green says. &ldquo;The year and a half that he spent working on the project paid off exponentially.&rdquo;<p>During the Ontario fire, which was contained by Tuesday, Oct. 23, the disaster portal logged 5,000 unique visitors and 50,000 hits.<p>&ldquo;They were definitely getting use out of it,&rdquo; Lickfett says.<p>He developed the portal through the National Science Foundation-supported RESCUE Project, which develops technology to assist first responders in an emergency. <p>Spearheaded by UCI and directed by Sharad Mehrotra, computer science professor, the project brings together researchers at five other universities: UC San Diego, University of Colorado at Boulder, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, University of Maryland and Brigham Young University. <p>Project leaders also work with local businesses and authorities, such as fire and police departments, interested in using the new technology.<p>&ldquo;There are lots of different research projects in RESCUE; we wanted one that has impact in the real world,&rdquo; Lickfett says. &ldquo;The disaster portal allowed me to work on the research side of the project, then see how it&rsquo;s used in a real situation. Those two things don&rsquo;t always go together.&rdquo;<p>The portal includes a Family Reunification Search that helps users track down missing family members, and a donations tab where users can post their needs and respond to calls for help.<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;ve now created a software package we can distribute to other cities,&rdquo; Lickfett says. &ldquo;After Ontario, we think the system is stable and useful.&rdquo; And it can save lives.<br><TITLE>To the rescue</TITLE>

</div>
</blockquote>
